Description¶

The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of unique plants belonging to 12 species at several growth stages.

The ability to do so effectively can mean better crop yields and better stewardship of the environment.

Objective¶

To implement the techniques learnt during "Introduction to coomputer vision".

Data Description¶

  • Labels.csv : A csv formated file contains the labels for each images.
  • images.npy : A standard binary file format contains all the images needed for analysis.

Data Pre-processing¶

  • Resize the image to 100 X 100 format.
  • Convert all the image from RGB to Grey scale to build efficient model.
In [5]:
images_array = []
images_grey = []
images_blur = []
labels_array = df_labels.to_numpy()
column_names = ["Label", "Image", "Image_Grey", "Image_Blur"]
data_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=column_names)
ulabel_array = df_labels.groupby("Label").nunique().index
In [6]:
index = 0
for npy_image in npy_array:

    lbl = labels_array[index]

    resizeImage = cv2.resize(npy_image, (scale, scale))
    greyImage = cv2.cvtColor(resizeImage, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    blurImage = cv2.GaussianBlur(resizeImage, (5, 5), cv2.BORDER_DEFAULT)
    images_array.append(npy_image)
    images_grey.append(greyImage)
    images_blur.append(blurImage)

    data_df.loc[len(data_df.index)] = [lbl[0], npy_image, greyImage, blurImage]

    index += 1

def find_mean_img(full_mat, title):
    # calculate the average
    mean_img = np.mean(full_mat, axis=0)
    # reshape it back to a matrix
    # mean_img = mean_img.reshape((scale, scale))
    plt.imshow(mean_img, vmin=0, vmax=255, cmap="Greys_r")
    plt.title(f"Average {title}")
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()
    return mean_img

Model Building¶

This analysis will use following Deep Neural Networks:

  • ANN (Artificial Neural Network - fully connected)
  • CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)

Artificial Neural Network (ANN)¶

Model 1: Fully connected ANN.

Model Architectuure¶

  • ANN has following characteristics.
    • Three fully connected dense layer with 512, 128 and 12 neurons each.
      • Hidden layer has ReLU activation function.
      • Output layer has softmax activation function for classification.
    • One dropout layer with probability of 0.5 is added between dense layer to prevent overfitting
In [27]:
ann = Sequential()

ann.add(Flatten(input_shape=(scale, scale)))

# Adding a fully connected layer with 700 neurons
ann.add(Dense(units=512, activation="relu"))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.5
ann.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Adding a fully connected layer with 250 neurons
ann.add(Dense(units=128, activation="relu"))

# The final output layer with 12 neurons to predict the categorical classifcation
ann.add(Dense(units=12, activation="softmax"))

ann.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])

ann.summary()

Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

Model 2: Relu CNN with three layers in convnet, three layers in dense and one dropout only in the dense network.

Model Architecture¶

Model architecture consists of CNN and ANN layers.

  • CNN has following characteristics.

    • Three convolution (Conv2D) layers
      • Each layer has 32 filters
      • Each filter is of size 3 X 3
      • ReLU activation function is used for learning weights
      • "same" padding tries to pad evenly left and right with zeros to preserve the spatial dimension.
    • Three max pooling layer with the size of 2X2 is affed between convolution layer to downsamples the input along its spatial dimensions (height and width).

  • Data from the CNN is flattened before passing it to ANN.

    • Flattening is converting the data into a 1-dimensional array for inputting it to the next layer

  • ANN has following characteristics.

    • Three fully connected dense layer with 512, 128 and 12 neurons each.
      • Hidden layer has ReLU activation function.
      • Output layer has softmax activation function for classification.
    • One dropout layer with probability of 0.5 is added between dense layer to prevent overfitting.
In [32]:
# Initialising the CNN classifier
cnn = Sequential()

# Add a Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn.add(
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=(scale, scale, 1), activation="relu", padding="same")
)

# Add a Max Pooling layer of size 2X2
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Add another Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"))

# Adding another pooling layer
cnn.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

Data Augmentation¶

The purpose of data auugmentation is to reduce overfitting during learning process. ImageDataGenerator is used to generate batches of tensor image data with real-time data augmentation. Following data augumentation parameters are used.

  • Images are randomly rotated 10 degrees.
  • Images are randomly shifted 5% to the left or right(horizontal shifts).
  • Images are randomly shifted 5% to the up or down (vertical shifts).
  • Images are randomly zoom between 90% (zoom in) and 110% (zoom out).
  • Images are not randomly flipped horizontally or vertically.
  • 20% of images reserved for validation.
In [36]:
cnndatagen = ImageDataGenerator(

    height_shift_range=0.05,

    vertical_flip=False,

)

Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

Model 2: Relu CNN with one batch normalization in convnet and one dropout only in the dense network.

Model Architecture¶

Model architecture consists of CNN and ANN layers.

  • CNN has following characteristics.

    • Three convolution (Conv2D) layers
      • Each layer has 32 filters
      • Each filter is of size 3 X 3
      • ReLU activation function is used for learning weights
      • "same" padding tries to pad evenly left and right with zeros to preserve the spatial dimension.
    • Three max pooling layer with the size of 2X2 is affed between convolution layer to downsamples the input along its spatial dimensions (height and width).
    • one layer to batch normalize the data is added.

  • Data from the CNN is flattened before passing it to ANN.

    • Flattening is converting the data into a 1-dimensional array for inputting it to the next layer

  • ANN has following characteristics.

    • Three fully connected dense layer with 512, 128 and 12 neurons each.
      • Hidden layer has ReLU activation function.
      • Output layer has softmax activation function for classification.
    • One dropout layer with probability of 0.5 is added between dense layer to prevent overfitting.
In [42]:
# Initialising the CNN classifier
cnn1 = Sequential()

# Add a Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn1.add(
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), input_shape=(scale, scale, 1), activation="relu", padding="same")
)

# Add a layer that normalizes its inputs
cnn1.add(BatchNormalization())

# Add a Max Pooling layer of size 2X2
cnn1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Add another Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn1.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same"))

# Adding another pooling layer
cnn1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Add another Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn1.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="valid"))

# Adding another pooling layer
cnn1.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Flattening the layer before fully connected layers
cnn1.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected layer with 512 neurons#
cnn1.add(Dense(units=512, activation="relu"))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.5
cnn1.add(Dropout(0.5))

# Adding a fully connected layer with 128 neurons
cnn1.add(Dense(units=128, activation="relu"))

# The final output layer with 10 neurons to predict the categorical classifcation
cnn1.add(Dense(units=12, activation="softmax"))

cnn1.summary()

Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)¶

Model 2: LeakyReLU CNN with no batch normalization and dropout in both Convolution and Dense network

Model Architecture¶

CNN has following characteristics.

  • Three convolution (Conv2D) layers
    • Each layer has 16 filters
    • Each filter is of size 5 X 5
    • LeakyReLU activation function is used for learning weights
    • "same" padding tries to pad evenly left and right with zeros to preserve the spatial dimension.
  • Three dropout laye with probability of 0.25 is added between convolution layer to prevent overfitting.
  • Three max pooling layer with the size of 2X2 is affed between convolution layer to downsamples the input along its spatial dimensions (height and width).

Data from the CNN is flattened before passing it to ANN.

  • Flattening is converting the data into a 1-dimensional array for inputting it to the next layer

ANN has following characteristics.

  • Three fully connected dense layer with 512, 256 and 12 neurons each.
    • Hidden layer has LeakyReLU activation function.
    • Output layer has softmax activation function for classification.
In [56]:
# Initialising the CNN classifier
cnn2 = Sequential()

# Add a Convolution layer with 32 kernels of 3X3 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn2.add(
    Conv2D(
        16,
        (5, 5),
        input_shape=(scale, scale, 1),
        activation=LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1),
        padding="same",
    )
)

# Adding dropout with probability 0.25
cnn2.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Add a Max Pooling layer of size 2X2
cnn2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Add another Convolution layer with 16 kernels of 5X5 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn2.add(Conv2D(16, (5, 5), activation=LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1), padding="same"))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.25
cnn2.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Adding another pooling layer
cnn2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Add another Convolution layer with 16 kernels of 5X5 shape with activation function ReLU
cnn2.add(Conv2D(16, (5, 5), activation=LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1), padding="valid"))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.25
cnn2.add(Dropout(0.25))

# Adding another pooling layer
cnn2.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

# Flattening the layer before fully connected layers
cnn2.add(Flatten())

# Adding a fully connected layer with 512 neurons
cnn2.add(Dense(units=512, activation=LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)))

# Adding dropout with probability 0.5
cnn2.add(Dropout(0.5))


# Adding a fully connected layer with 125628 neurons
cnn2.add(Dense(units=256, activation=LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1)))


# The final output layer with 10 neurons to predict the categorical classifcation
cnn2.add(Dense(units=12, activation="softmax"))

Model insights.¶

  • Out of four models, build "Relu CNN with three layers in convnet, three layers in dense and one dropout only in the dense network." performs the best.
  • Poor accuracy seedlings are undersampled.
    • common wheat,
    • Black grass, and
    • Shepherds Purse.
  • Imbalanced seedling causes poor accuracy.
  • Batch normalization, max pooling, and dropout significantly impact the train and test accuracy. Therefore, more analysis is required to find the optimal layer.
  • ImageDataAuugmentation is a handy tool that has many parameters to tune the data set for better prediction.

Scope of Improvement¶

  • There is significant scope for improvement in the test accuracy and F1 score of the CNN model chosen here.
  • Different architectures with tuned layers can obtain better accuracy.
  • More analysis is needed to tune the Image data augmentation parameter.
  • More research and analysis is needed on imbalanced data set to improve the accuracy of undersampled data. (class_weight)

Conclusion and key takeaways¶

  • CNN works well with image datasets since it retains spatial structure.
  • Structure of the image has a significant impact on the CNN prediction.
    • Structured image like x-ray, brain scans, etc. has some predefined structure.
    • Technique like mean image calculation, etc., has a positive impact on the analysis.
  • Hyperparameter tuning is the single most determinant of model performance.
  • Model architecture determines the quality of the prediction.
  • Following parameters are crucial in model architecture.
    • Filter Size
    • Strides
    • Number of Conv2D layers
    • Number of MaxPool2D layers
    • Proper mix of dropout and batch normalization.
  • Data augmentation technique significantly improves the model accuracy.
  • ANN does not work well with image data.
    • It flattens the image and loses its spatial structure.
